London : proper noun, singular, object of the preposition "to"

Sentence: Why are the streets so quiet today?
why : interrogative adverb, adjunct indicating reason
are : verb "be", present tense, third person plural
the : definite article, plural
streets : common noun, plural, subject of the verb "are"
so : adverb of degree, modifying the adjective "quiet"
quiet : adjective, subject complement describing "streets"
today : adverb of time, adjunct indicating when the state exists

Sentence: How many students passed the final exam?
how : interrogative adverb, part of the phrase "how many"
many : interrogative determiner, modifying the noun "students"
students : common noun, plural, subject of the verb "passed"
passed : verb "pass", past tense, active voice
the : definite article, singular
final : adjective, modifying the noun "exam"
exam : common noun, singular, direct object of the verb "passed"

Sentence: Which color do you prefer for the walls?
which : interrogative determiner, modifying the noun "color"
color : common noun, singular, direct object of the verb "prefer"
do : auxiliary verb "do", present tense, used for question formation
you : personal pronoun, second person, subject of the verb "prefer"
prefer : main verb "prefer", base form
for : preposition indicating purpose or association
the : definite article, plural
walls : common noun, plural, object of the preposition "for"
